    "ui_concept": {
      "type": "custom-liquid",
      "settings": {
        "section_visibility": "always",
        "custom_liquid": "<div class=\"ui-feature-shell\">\n  <section class=\"ui-section\">\n    <div class=\"ui-wrap\">\n      <div class=\"ui-section-head\">\n        <p class=\"ui-kicker\">The Concept</p>\n        <h2>What is a Universal In-Ear Monitor?</h2>\n        <p>A Universal In-Ear Monitor is studio sound in a shell built to welcome any listener. Where a custom is moulded to a single anatomy, a universal is shaped to fit gracefully across many — sealed by interchangeable tips, voiced to the same reference targets as our flagships. The result is reference performance, ready to listen, the moment it arrives.</p>\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"ui-article-body\">\n        <div class=\"ui-article-copy\">\n          <h3>A monitor, not an earbud</h3>\n          <p>The word “monitor” does the heavy lifting here. A consumer earbud is tuned for casual amusement — frequently with an exaggerated V-curve that flatters but obscures. A studio or stage monitor is tuned for honesty: you hear what the microphone captured, what the mix engineer intended, what the artist meant. Every AAW universal follows the same reference tuning targets as our custom line — uncompromised, unmistakable.</p>\n          <p>A universal IEM is a rigid resin shell — injection-moulded or 3D-printed — that houses balanced armatures, dynamic drivers, or both. Sound travels from each driver through precision-bore tubing to a single nozzle. You choose the tip; the tip creates the seal; and once the seal is right, the monitor delivers its full performance — from sub-bass weight to upper-treble air — with stereo imaging that holds steady all the way through.</p>\n          <p>Universals are the most welcoming entry into reference-grade personal audio. They are used by working musicians as backups to their customs, by audiophiles tasting different signatures across a single evening, and by anyone who wants studio sound without the wait of a custom build.</p>\n        </div>\n        <figure class=\"ui-article-figure\">\n          <img src=\"{{ 'a3h-lux-pair-wide.jpg' | asset_img_url: '1200x' }}\" alt=\"AAW universal in-ear monitor pair showing standardised shell design\" loading=\"lazy\">\n          <figcaption><b>AAW universal range</b><span>Standardised shells, identical drivers, identical tuning. The path from our customs to our universals is far shorter than the price suggests.</span></figcaption>\n        </figure>\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"ui-subhead\">A short history of the in-ear monitor</div>\n      <ul class=\"ui-timeline\" style=\"margin-top:0;\">\n        <li><b>1980s — The stage wedge problem</b>Floor monitors were loud, prone to feedback, and inconsistent from night to night. Musicians began searching for a better way to hear themselves on stage.</li>\n        <li><b>1995 — The custom IEM is born</b>Jerry Harvey builds the first custom in-ear monitor for drummer Alex Van Halen, marrying hearing-aid shell techniques with miniature balanced armature drivers. The category begins.</li>\n        <li><b>2000s — Universals reach the world</b>Shure, Westone, Ultimate Ears and others introduce universal-fit versions of their stage monitors. Audiophiles take notice. The IEM is no longer just a stage tool — it becomes a listening instrument.</li>\n        <li><b>2014 — AAW is founded in Singapore</b>Advanced AcousticWerkes begins building custom and universal IEMs from a single workshop. Hybrid architectures, tubeless designs, and a particular kind of musical tuning quickly define the AAW signature.</li>\n        <li><b>Today — Universals rival customs</b>With materials like AAW’s LiquidMorph tips, advanced multi-driver hybrids, and switchable tuning, a thoughtfully designed universal can deliver almost the entire custom experience — at a lower entry, with no wait at all.</li>\n      </ul>\n    </div>\n  </section>\n</div>",
        "content_width": "large",
        "text_alignment": "left",
        "color_scheme": "primary",
        "top_space_desktop": 0,
        "bottom_space_desktop": 0,
